{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600581/1930100501/0181.xml":{"full_text":"C-12\nCOMMODITY BUYING\nIS SEEN AS NEED\nFederation of Labor Presi\ndent Outlines Policies to\nAmeliorate Business.\nMore buying of commodities will\nstabilize business conditions, William\nGreen, president of the American Fed\neration of Labor, declared yesterday.\nIn the monthly survey of business\nconditions, published by the labor fed\neration. the labor leader suggests that\nincreased purchases of commodities is\nthe answer to the business depression\nat present gripping the Nation and\nurges the public to \u201cstock up\u201d on goods\nnecessary for sustenance and business\nPolicies are Suggested.\n\u201cBusiness men,\u201d Green said, \u201ccan\nhasten revival and improve their own\ntrade without undue risk by such\npolicies s these:\n\u201c1. Cut overhead costs (without re\nducing wages) by Improving equipment\nand eliminating waste.\n\"2. Order ahead; start to work up a\nnormal Spring supply.\n\u201c3. Improve quality of product and\nreduce prices.\n\"4. Stimulate trade by advertising\nand special efforts.\u201d\nGreen added these measures \u201cwill\nincrease employment and put products\nwithin reach of this year\u2019s.low incomes\u201d\nand wage earners \u201ccan help produce\nbetter articles at lower cost by improv\ning the quality of their work and in\ncreasing efficiency.'\u2019\nSays Opportunity Begins.\n\u201cFor the first time in many months,\u201d\nGreen said, \u201cbusiness opportunity is\nopening. Fundamental adjustments\nhave been made, favorable signs are\nappearing. Our foreign trade shows,\nsigns of improving, wholesale^ prices are\nmore stable, retail prices 'are down\nnearer the point where workers can buy,\nthe outlook for employment is better\nand that means increased workers\u2019 buy\ning power. Stores see their customers\ncoming back. Opportunity is here for\nthose who are ready to make the best\nof it\u201d\nGreen asserted that the course of\nbusiness in the \u201ccoming four weeks will\ndetermine the prospects for next Win\nter\u201d and that \u201cif we want to avoid a\nWinter like last year we must plan\nfor it now by using every intelligent\nmeans of promoting business revival.\u201d\nCHILLUMHEIGHTS\nELECTIONS HELD\nThomas W. Joy Is Named Presi\ndent of Citizens\u2019 Association\nat Meeting.\nThomas W. Joy was re-elected presi\ndent of the Chillum Heights Citizens\u2019\nAssociation at the annual meeting for\nthe election of officers, in the Joseph\nR. Keene School Friday night. All pther\nofficers were re-elected. They are:\nE. M. Barry, vice president; Arthur\nW. Clime, secretary and George W.\nCostln, treasurer. J. B. Hopkins and\nEugene Blanchard were elected dele\ngates to the Federation of Citizens\u2019\nAssociations.\nA resolution was adopted asking the\nDistrict Commissioners to close a trash\ndump near Terra Cotta, in northeast\nWashington. Several times in the past\nfew months the dump has caught fire,\nconstituting a nuisance, it was charged.\nThe meeting last night was the first\none of this season held by the\nassociation.\nGEN. BURNHAM RITES\nAT ARLINGTON TOMORROW\nRetired Infantry Officer, Who Died\nin California, Received Num\nber of Decorations.\nFuneral sendees will be held at the\nArlington National Cemetery Monday\nmorning at 10 o\u2019clock for Maj. Gen.\nWilliam P. Burnham, U. S. A., retired,\nwho died in the Letterman General\nHospital. San Francisco, September 27.\nBom in Scranton, Pa., January 10,\n1860, Gen. Burnham served in the ranks\nfrom 1881 to 1883, when he was com\nmissioned a second lieutenant of In\nfantry. He served in the Spanish War\nof 1898, in Hawaii, the Philippines,\nPanama, at various posts in the United\nStates and in France. During the World\nWar he commanded the 82d Division\nduring the St. Mihiel and Meuse-\nArgonne offensives and was promoted to\nthe grade of major general in the\nNational Army.\nLater he was military attache at\nAthens and served on the Inter-Allied\nMilitary Commission in Greece. He re\nceived a number of decorations, includ\ning the British Companion of the Bath,\nthe French Legion of Honor and the\nCroix de Guerre and the Greek Medal\nfor Valor. In January, 1924, he was\nretired for age and since resided in\nCalifornia.\nMRS. MORRISON AT HEAD\nOF D. C. WAR MOTHERS\nWas Re-Elected President for An\nother Term\u2014Full Board of\nOfficers Chosen,\nMrs. Kate Morrison was re-elected\npresident of the District of Columbia\nChapter. American War Mothers, Fri\nday night at a meeting in the Hamilton\nHotel.\nMrs. E. C. Wagner, recording secre\ntary, and Mrs. May D. Lightfoot, cor\nresponding secretary, were also re\nelected.\nOther officers elected were Mrs. Lucy\nCash, first vice president; Mrs. Ida\nSmith, second vice president; Mrs. C.\nB. Domch, third vice president; Mrs.\nJohn Spengler. fourth vice president;\nMrs. Mary T. Shanahan, treasurer;\nMrs. Mary L. Fisher, custodian of rec\nords; Mrs. Fannie Smith, historian, and\nMrs. Sarah E. Deeds, chaplain.\nDEATH CALL.ED SUICIDE\nCertificate Issued That James B.\nGadbury Took Own Life.\nA certificate of suicide was signed by\nDeputy Coroner Joseph Rodgers in\nthe death of James B. Gadbury,\n39-year-old disabled war veteran\nand former newspaper man, who ended\nhis life Friday by drinking poison\nand hanging himself from a tree on\nthe estate of James Parmalee In the\n3100 block of Macomb street.\nGadbury had been 111 for several\nmonths, Dr. Rodgers learned. His body\nwas found by Raymond Knight, an\nemploye on the Parmalee estate, and\nSpencer E. Darr of Ballston, Va. The\nman lived with his wife, Mrs. Helen\nGadbury, in the 2900 block Connecticut\navenue.\nDeplores High Cost of Amusement.\nOXFORD. England, October 4 (iP).\u2014\nDean Inge is gloomy about the enor\nmous sums spent on pleasure and amuse\nment. In an address in behalf of the\nnational savings movement, he said,\nthe amount spent last year on amuse\nment In America was estimated at $21,-\n946,000.000, and \u201ctwo years of Amerl\ncafi\u2019play would suffice to pay the whole\nnational debt.\u201d j*.\nA STARTLING OFFER FOR MONDAY\nEither of These Fine Suites at an Unheard of Price!\nHandsome^\nI Woodrose Mohair 10-Piece Walnut Wit\nI Living Room Suite- Dining Room Suite |Jj llljl\nV I A most unusually attractive living room U TMjH ,\u201ea*foy J\nsuite. Well constructed and beautifully ThTs beautifully designed dining room II S|r j\nupholstered in woodrose mohair. Rich suite, illustrated, is of genuine walnut Mjr\nm I carvings on the wood frame greatly en- veneer over a gumwood foundation, and\nn I hance its beauty. A long, luxuriously further beautified with rich overlays. The 3ji 'T\nIS; J I comfortable sofa, high-back armchair suite consists of a 42x54-inch extension H 1!\"\nBj rj\\ ]i/' j I and chair comprise this suite, which' table, 66-inch buffet, grilled-door china g\nI\\l s tted loose, reversible, spring- cabinet, enclosed server, host chair and 2rl)\nfilled seat cushions with beautiful rayon five side chairs. Chairs are upholstered in I\nConvenient Terms Easily Arranged 3\n\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0nil\u2014\nP \u2018\u2018ZION\u201d LACE \u2019jpp\nFnnged^Panels\nj\u00a7Psl|j High Grade\nDamask window drapes with 50-inch fringed valance |\u00bbfl -iZ SeamleSS AXUlillSter RugfS\nin rich, deep red combined witn gold, blue, rose and u I\nsoft shades of green or gold. Pair.... I I 9x12 ft. or 8.3x10.6 ft.\n100| Double Wool Blankets Six-Piece Oriental Walnut Bedroom Suite X A .75\nFluffy 100% all-wool double The suite illustrated above is one worthy of use in any\nblankets in combination of rose <UQ 7 5 room It is beautifully designed and finished in \u2014g\nInrnwTTnPi Ji Oriental walnut with attractive moire walnut overlays and /J* M m Scatter Rill'S to match\u2014\u2022 OCT\nand white plaid, blue, tan, S consists of a most decorative return-end wood bed. 1 07 Cj.\nyellow or green dresser, French vanity, deck chest of draw